<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="280" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,153,647]" pageId="9" pageNumber="280">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,441,467]" pageId="9" pageNumber="280">Etymology.</emphasis>
The new species name is in honor of a friend, Prof. Dr. Allan Paulo Moreira dos Santos, a Brazilian trichopterologist who was one of collectors of the 
<typeStatus box="[714,762,477,503]" pageId="9" pageNumber="280">type</typeStatus>
series.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,153,647]" pageId="9" pageNumber="280">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,273,513,539]" pageId="9" pageNumber="280">Notes.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Gonçalves &amp; Dietrich &amp; Takiya, 2019" authorityName="Gonçalves &amp; Dietrich &amp; Takiya" authorityYear="2019" box="[280,389,513,539]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pentoffia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="santosi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[280,297,514,539]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="280">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[310,389,514,539]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="280">santosi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[396,485,513,539]" pageId="9" pageNumber="280">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[396,485,513,539]" pageId="9" pageNumber="280" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Dietrich, 2004" authorityName="Dietrich" authorityYear="2004" box="[630,889,513,539]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pentoffia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigra">
<emphasis box="[630,647,514,539]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="280">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[661,722,514,539]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="280">nigra</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Dietrich, C. H." box="[728,889,513,539]" pageId="9" pageNumber="280" pagination="455 - 487" refId="ref5482" refString="Dietrich, C. H. (2004) Phylogeny of the leafhopper subfamily Evacanthinae with a review of Neotropical species and notes on related groups (Hemiptera: Membracoidea: Cicadellidae). Systematic Entomology, 29, 455 - 487, https: // doi. prg / 10.1111 / j. 0307 - 6970.2004.00250. x" type="journal article" year="2004">
Dietrich, 
<quantity box="[833,889,513,539]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.090159999999999" pageId="9" pageNumber="280" unit="in" value="2004.0">2004</quantity>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
in the tubular and dorsally curved aedeagal shaft and shape, length, and curvature of the atrial processes. However, 
<taxonomicName authority="Gonçalves &amp; Dietrich &amp; Takiya, 2019" authorityName="Gonçalves &amp; Dietrich &amp; Takiya" authorityYear="2019" box="[901,1011,549,575]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pentoffia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="santosi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[901,918,550,575]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="280">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[932,1011,550,575]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="280">santosi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1019,1110,549,575]" pageId="9" pageNumber="280">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1019,1110,549,575]" pageId="9" pageNumber="280" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dietrich" authorityYear="2004" box="[1260,1353,549,575]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pentoffia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigra">
<emphasis box="[1260,1277,550,575]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="280">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1292,1353,550,575]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="280">nigra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by: (1) having the inverted Y-shaped macula on crown; (2) aedeagus atrial processes that do not cross each other and not twisted apically; and (3) aedeagus shaft with median region expanded laterally.
</paragraph>
